lement is devoted to colonial ethnohistory. Four of the eleven chapters review research and ethnohistorical resources for Guatemala, South Yucatan, North Yucatan, and Oaxaca, areas that received less attention than the central Mexican area in the original Guide to Ethnohistorical Sources (HMAI vols. 12-15). Six substantive and problem-oriented studies cover the use of colonial texts in the study of pre-colonial Mayan languages; political and economic organization in the valleys of Mexico, Puebla-Tlaxcala, and Morelos; urban-rural relations in the Basin of Mexico; kinship and social organization in colonial Tenochtitlan; tlamemes and transport in colonial central Mexico; and land tenure and titles in central Mexico as reflected in colonial codices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEthnohistory. 0aIndians of Central America. 0aIndians of Mexico. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBricker, Victoria Reifler, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarmack, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChance, John K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharlton, Thomas H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarriss, Nancy M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, H. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHassig, Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHicks, Frederic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Grant D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJusteson, John S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKellog